aws::graph::propositions: Piaggio P.180 Avanti Aircraft Delivery and Development Information
The 100th Piaggio P.180 Avanti aircraft was delivered in October 2005.
The 150th Piaggio P.180 Avanti aircraft was delivered in May 2008.
Piaggio reported that the Avanti and Avanti II fleets had logged over 500,000 flying hours as of October 2010.
An improved Piaggio P.180 Avanti II obtained European certification in November 2005.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II obtained U.S. certification in November 2005.
70 Piaggio P.180 Avanti II planes had been ordered six months after certification.
36 Piaggio P.180 Avanti II planes were ordered by Avantair.
Piaggio P.180 Avanti II received type approval for Russia in 2011.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II featured uprated Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6A-66B turboprop engines.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II flies about 18 km/h (11 mph) faster than the original Avanti.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II has better fuel economy than the original Avanti.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II has an all-new "glass panel" avionics suite from Rockwell Collins.
The Rockwell Collins avionics suite reduced cockpit clutter in the Piaggio P.180 Avanti II.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays show heading information.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays show attitude information.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays show navigation information.
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays add collision avoidance (TCAS).
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays add ground proximity (TAWS).
The Piaggio P.180 Avanti II's flat panel color liquid crystal displays add real-time graphic weather depiction.

text:
The 100th aircraft was delivered in October 2005 and the 150th in May 2008. Piaggio reported that, as of October 2010, the Avanti and Avanti II fleets had logged over 500,000 flying hours.
An improved Avanti II obtained European and U.S. certification in November 2005. Six months later, 70 planes had been ordered, including 36 by Avantair. Avanti II received type approval for Russia in 2011. The Avanti II featured uprated Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6A-66B turboprop engines and flies about 18 km/h (11 mph) faster, with better fuel economy; and an all-new "glass panel" avionics suite from Rockwell Collins reduced cockpit clutter. In addition to heading, attitude and navigation information, flat panel color liquid crystal displays add collision avoidance (TCAS), ground proximity (TAWS) and real-time graphic weather depiction.
